I've been going back and forth if I wanted to share my story. A part of me feels the internet has conditioned us to be so transparent; leaving no room for privacy. However, I know I am friends with a lot of women on facebook. Some are mothers and some are not, and maybe there are some who have experienced or are experiencing what I am as well. My hope is for others to find strength within my words, as I have found strength within the words of others. Walking away from this situation has left me with a new found respect towards all women and our ability to create the gift of life. What a blessing!

I was 6 weeks pregnant when I found out that my body had miscarried. It may not seem like a long time, however, my outlook on life has changed forever. Although I may not know the answer yet, I know everything truly happens for a reason. I confidently believe God has other plans for me right now and for those who may be going through the same experience.

For those women who have babies, I envy you. Your ability to do the coolest thing in the world: grow a life from within. Never take that ability for granted. Women, we truly run the world.

I'd like to share a poem expressing this vulnerable time. I know there are other women who have felt the same pain and confusion as I have and I can't stress enough that we are not alone:

I met you yesterday.
It was sooner than I anticipated. But it didnâ€™t make me love you any less.
I never got to hold you or hear your heart beat, but I felt you inside me.
People ask me, â€œhow did you knowâ€. And as clichÃ© as it sounds, you just do. A Motherâ€™s instinct, if you will.

I keep asking myself, was it something I did. But deep down I know, this was an act from God.
A gift is a gift regardless of how long I had you. And a life of any sort is truly a blessing.

I wish I appreciated you more. I wish that I embraced the short time we had together.
A guilt that will never subside.

Yesterday I met you.
Exactly one week and a day after I confirmed you were there.
I found a satisfaction in watching you exit my body; knowing now you would never have to suffer in this world.

The week we spent together, felt like a lifetime. Time truly stopped.
The love I felt for you consumed me and I immediately began wanting to protect you.
I started to imagine what life would be for you.
Am I capable of raising you? Am I capable of giving you the perfect world you deserve to be born into?
My fear of failing consumed me.
You deserve everlasting happiness and security, and I began to doubt my ability to provide that for you.

When the doctors told me the news, you reintroduced me to God.
I was reminded how out of my control life truly is, which caused me to find faith.
I started to forget the fears and doubts.
Slowly, I regained my self worth; embracing the unconditional love I had for you. Realizing, I was chosen to have you.

You gave me a purpose in life, something I have always struggled to find.
You made me a version of myself that I have never been: a momma. And your momma I will always be.

I met you yesterday.
A day I will never forget.
